@lmittmann Please take a stance on this now.

Are you going to rename your library? You are clashing with both Python.NET and IronPython and are causing confusion for people using `pip` directly. If not, please at least say so now and we will put the corresponding information into our Readme and entry page.

Please don't try to hack around this by capturing `import System` or `clr.AddReference`.

I still don't follow.  The error seems to come from this code:

```
    inline std::array<unsigned int,4> cpuid(int) 
    {
        return std::array<unsigned int,4>{};
    } 
    inline bool cpu_has_sse2_instructions()   { return 0!=(cpuid(1)[3]&(1<<26)); }
```

That code doesn't have anything to do with any kind of SIMD or hardware specific features whatsoever.

I deleted all trash from work computer, cleaned it with CCleaner and reboot. Then I installed TortoiseHG 2.3.1. Switch on mercurial_keyring. Still crash on command "hg pull". So it is a problem exactly on my work PC. I showed it to our Admin. He finds a solution - to use bat-file hg.bat:
{{{
runas /savecred /user:vosipov@fastlane.local "hg %*"
}}}

It says that problem in Windows UAC. Though I am admin, when I launch "hg pull" the UAC sometimes doesn't know that I am admin. When launch hg from my account with the command "runas /savecred /user:vosipov@fastlane.local "hg pull"" then no crash. It uses ntdll.dll which works under system SID and which uses hg which runs under users SID.

