In this case I propose we test to see if `channel_urls` is not a `dict`; and if not, convert it internally to that function. Something like this (but I'm not at my desk so this is not copy and paste code)
```
if not isinstance(channel_urls, dict):
    channel_urls = {url:(config.canonical_channel_name(url),k) for k, url in enumerate(channel_urls)}
```

@ankurankan The CPDs created using the fit method create state name dicts automatically. So for predict we need these state names. There is an internal call to ```Inference``` class in the predict method and therefore it need the state names dict as an input parameter. 

An another way would be to wrap the return value of the predict method. It returns a pandas data frame. This case does not exist in ```StateNameDecorator```, so it will have to be added. Since, currently pgmpy models do need a state name dict, a case has to be added in the state name decorator where it checks for a state name dict in the CPDs associated with the model as well.

But I feel the former method is better because anyway the ```predict``` method calls ```Inference.map_query``` which uses the state name functionality appropriately.

